  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: The Mane Is Weekly Homework" imageAlt="Sheltie puppy having its double coat line-brushed" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>The Sheltie coat is the Collie look on subscription: brush 2 to 3 times a week down to the skin, working in layers, with daily sessions during the twice-yearly coat blows. Skip a fortnight and mats form quietly behind the ears and in the trousers. A tidy-up groom every 6 to 8 weeks keeps things civilised, and, the double-coat rule as always, never shave it; the coat insulates against our heat when kept brushed, and shaving damages regrowth.</p>
      <p>Expect real hair in the flat. The vacuum joins the family, the lint roller lives by the door, and Sheltie people decide it's worth it, but decide with open eyes.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Sheltie Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Sheltie puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Sheltie goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. The Sheltie health points worth knowing: eye conditions run in herding lines, Collie eye anomaly and progressive retinal atrophy, so ask any seller about eye checks, as you should for every herding breed; hip dysplasia appears occasionally; and, the one to write down, many Shelties carry the MDR1 gene variant, which makes certain common drugs, including some dewormers and anti-diarrhoeals, dangerous at normal doses. Tell every vet your dog is a Sheltie before any prescription; a simple cheek-swab test settles it definitively.</p>
      <p>Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. See the puppy health checks explained guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <div class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="The Voice: Every Honest Sheltie Page Mentions It" imagePosition="none" variant="card">
      <p>On the croft, barking was the Sheltie's job description: move the sheep, alert the croft, repeat. In a flat, that professional instinct meets lift doors, corridor footsteps and delivery riders, and an untrained Sheltie will provide full commentary. This is the breed's one genuine flat-living challenge, and pretending otherwise sells dogs badly.</p>
      <p>The fix is two-part and reliable: enough physical and mental work that there's no restless energy left to narrate with, and early, consistent quiet-training, rewarding silence, never yelling over the noise, which a sensitive Sheltie reads as joining in. Started in puppyhood, most Shelties settle into an acceptable watchdog-announcement level. Started never, the neighbours will introduce themselves.</p>
      <div slot="side" class="clay h-full bg-[var(--color-peach-100)] p-6 sm:p-8">
        <p class="text-xs font-bold uppercase text-[var(--color-cream-500)]" style="letter-spacing: 0.08em;">Quiet-training basics</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3">
          {[
            'Exercise first; a tired Sheltie narrates less',
            'Reward silence, never shout over barking',
            'Start week one; the free lesson covers it',
          ].map((fact) => (
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-cream-700)]">
              <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" class="mt-0.5 shrink-0 text-[var(--color-coral-500)]" aria-hidden="true">
                <path d="M20 6 9 17l-5-5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" />
              </svg>
              {fact}
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>
    </CaptionedBlock>

    <PawTrail bg="bg-[var(--color-surface)]" colorClass="text-[var(--color-coral-300)]" />
  </div>

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Sheltie's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Sheltie puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene5} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Sheltie explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about how our free home delivery and setup works.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm, gentle and predictable; this sensitive breed reads household stress like a book, so a quiet settling window pays off doubly. Fixed feeding routine, toilet pads where we placed them, soft voices.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks and the studying begins. Book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer this week without fail, and start the quiet-training pattern immediately; for a Sheltie both are foundational, not optional. See what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

